And solidarity for the
suffering of these people,

50:14.330 --> 50:15.960
But we can't think
that the suffering

50:15.964 --> 50:17.364
Has fallen out of the sky,

50:17.365 --> 50:19.125
And they're just
particularly benighted

50:19.133 --> 50:22.271
Because they happen to have been
the subject of that, right.

50:22.272 --> 50:24.499
There are policies
that have been enacted.

50:24.504 --> 50:26.504
There are decisions
that have been made.

50:26.506 --> 50:28.206
There are bombs
that have been dropped.

50:28.207 --> 50:31.167
As a consequence of which,
these millions of people

50:31.176 --> 50:33.136
Are destitute in
the way that they are,

50:33.144 --> 50:36.346
And we have to allow
them to tell that story.

50:36.347 --> 50:40.247
Do you think the
Russian, Syrian, french,

50:40.250 --> 50:43.718
British bombing of
Syria will save it?

50:43.719 --> 50:45.119
No, no, no.

50:45.120 --> 50:47.287
It's not the solution.

50:47.288 --> 50:51.088
You can't protect someone
by killing someone else.

50:58.564 --> 51:01.202
In international waters,
in the gulf of tonkin,

51:01.203 --> 51:03.169
Destroyers of the
United States navy

51:03.170 --> 51:06.397
Are assigned routine
patrols from time to time.

51:06.403 --> 51:09.338
Sunday, August the 2nd, 1964,

51:09.339 --> 51:12.269
The destroyer, Maddox,
was on such a patrol.

51:12.275 --> 51:15.305
Shortly after noon,
the calm of the day is broken

51:15.311 --> 51:17.081
As general quarters sound.

51:18.512 --> 51:20.752
In a deliberate
and unprovoked action,

51:20.753 --> 51:24.648
Three north Vietnam pt boats
unleash a torpedo attack

51:24.651 --> 51:26.351
Against the Maddox.

51:26.352 --> 51:28.692
A classic example of
I.F. Stone's ability

51:28.693 --> 51:32.387
To ferret out something
when no one else was doing it

51:32.390 --> 51:36.960
Was the gulf of tonkin excuse
for going into Vietnam.

52:07.656 --> 52:12.486
Three weeks after we had
the so-called attack

52:12.494 --> 52:16.697
By the north Vietnamese,
Izzy read all the after reports,

52:16.698 --> 52:20.298
And he said, "where... where's
the debris if we had been hit?"

52:20.301 --> 52:22.331
Why isn't there more
being talked about?"

52:22.336 --> 52:24.766
And he said there were
all kinds of excuses

52:24.771 --> 52:27.241
Why this little, tiny
country would go against

52:27.242 --> 52:28.870
The largest fleet in the world,

52:28.874 --> 52:32.509
Except the fact that it
might have been provoked.

52:32.510 --> 52:35.680
All of the media was just
following it right into war,

52:35.681 --> 52:38.049
As was congress,
and I keep thinking

52:38.050 --> 52:41.248
If the mainstream media
had followed Izzy,

52:41.251 --> 52:43.751
We might not have had
that ten year disaster.

52:52.727 --> 52:55.427
We hadn't been able to
get it through our heads

52:55.429 --> 52:58.129
That this is a political war.

52:58.131 --> 52:59.531
All you have to ask yourself is

52:59.532 --> 53:03.132
Why is it that here
are Vietnamese

53:03.135 --> 53:04.665
On one side, on our side,

53:04.669 --> 53:07.569
And here are the same
Vietnamese on the other side.

53:07.571 --> 53:09.871
And on one side, they have
very little in the way of arms.

53:09.873 --> 53:13.111
They have no air force,
no napalm, no big boom-boom,

53:13.112 --> 53:15.009
And they really
fight magnificently.

53:15.010 --> 53:17.710
And on our side, you have
five times as many troops,

53:17.712 --> 53:20.750
All that equipment, all that
firepower, all that artillery,

53:20.751 --> 53:22.578
And they're not worth a damn.

53:22.583 --> 53:25.153
A lot of people protested
I.F. Stone's being on,

53:25.154 --> 53:27.722
Because can you imagine
he had the nerve

53:27.723 --> 53:31.356
To say things against
our war policy?

53:31.357 --> 53:32.857
Well, it was bold at the time

53:32.858 --> 53:36.327
When we were suffering
with all kinds of things.

53:36.328 --> 53:38.698
Assassinations,
and the Vietnam war,

53:38.699 --> 53:41.457
A subject on which stone
was quite brilliant,

53:41.466 --> 53:42.996
And how we got into it

53:43.000 --> 53:45.100
And how we were probably
never gonna get out of it

53:45.102 --> 53:46.572
The way we were
going and it was...

53:46.573 --> 53:48.938
Took guts to say those things.

53:48.939 --> 53:51.339
The extreme right and
the hate mail writers

53:51.341 --> 53:53.008
Were always ready to go.

53:53.009 --> 53:56.079
Ask any solider back from
Vietnam, he'll agree with me.

53:56.080 --> 53:58.508
I don't mean to say there
aren't brave men among them,

53:58.513 --> 54:01.448
And some good troops,
but on the whole,

54:01.449 --> 54:03.679
The men on one side are fighting

54:03.684 --> 54:06.354
And the men on the other side
don't care and are deserting.

54:06.355 --> 54:07.653
Why is this?

54:07.654 --> 54:09.423
Why, because the men
on the other side

54:09.424 --> 54:11.391
Feel they're
fighting for freedom.

54:11.392 --> 54:12.990
They're fighting
for freedom from...

54:12.991 --> 54:16.691
From domination by the white
man, and by the westerner.

54:16.694 --> 54:19.764
I.F. Stone would be debunking
the official fictions

54:19.765 --> 54:22.333
As soon as government
was spewing them.

54:22.334 --> 54:25.432
Whether it was during
the Joe McCarthy era,

54:25.435 --> 54:28.365
Or all of the lies
about Vietnam.

54:28.371 --> 54:30.571
You could read
Izzy stone within a week,

54:30.573 --> 54:32.773
And he was debunking
these fictions.

54:34.342 --> 54:37.578
We need to know
what governments do.

54:37.579 --> 54:39.709
We need to know what's real,

54:39.714 --> 54:42.714
And we need to know
what's bullshit.

54:43.782 --> 54:45.482
And that's the biggest problem,

54:45.484 --> 54:49.252
And Izzy was great

54:49.253 --> 54:51.953
At saying, "hey, I checked."

54:51.955 --> 54:54.085
This is bullshit."

54:54.090 --> 54:57.559
Just as Izzy wrote and
published I.F. Stone's weekly

54:57.560 --> 54:59.590
Out of his home with his wife,

54:59.595 --> 55:01.655
Esther, managing the accounts,

55:01.663 --> 55:05.499
Tom Engelhardt with his
blog, Tomdispatch. Com,

55:05.500 --> 55:08.530
Is another example
of how a journalist

55:08.536 --> 55:11.236
Working from
a small office at home

55:11.238 --> 55:13.638
Can reach a very wide audience

55:13.640 --> 55:16.508
With independent
reporting and analysis.

55:16.509 --> 55:17.978
On how I started Tomdispatch,

55:17.979 --> 55:20.637
You'd have to go back
to literally to 9/11,

55:20.646 --> 55:23.576
And our news began
to constrict, you know,

55:23.582 --> 55:26.020
In a way I hadn't seen, even
at the height of the cold war,

55:26.021 --> 55:27.477
As far as I was concerned.

55:27.485 --> 55:30.445
And I suddenly
realized that out there,

55:30.454 --> 55:31.991
There was another kind of news.

55:31.992 --> 55:33.988
I started obsessively
gathering this stuff,

55:33.990 --> 55:36.460
And then, and writing
little comments,

55:36.461 --> 55:38.889
And my little comments
became a kind of commentary

55:38.894 --> 55:41.132
And then this was the
miracle of the internet,

55:41.133 --> 55:42.696
People started jumping on.

55:42.697 --> 55:44.427
People started writing me and
saying, "can I be on your list?"

55:44.432 --> 55:46.002
I didn't even really
know I had a list,

55:46.003 --> 55:48.100
And suddenly, I had
a list of 400 people

55:48.102 --> 55:51.340
Including journalists and I
mean, Susan Sontag wrote me,

55:51.341 --> 55:52.538
I mean, out of the blue.

55:52.539 --> 55:53.599
I didn't know Susan Sontag.

55:53.606 --> 55:55.166
I'm now almost 71.

55:55.174 --> 55:56.874
I'm plunged into,
I was from the beginning,

55:56.875 --> 55:59.175
Plunged into a world
of much younger people.

55:59.177 --> 56:00.807
I had no idea what I was doing,

56:00.811 --> 56:03.381
But I had been working
as a book editor

56:03.382 --> 56:04.680
With great writers for years.

56:04.681 --> 56:07.111
Chalmers Johnson,
all sorts of people.

56:07.116 --> 56:09.746
And I started asking them
once this thing started,

56:09.751 --> 56:12.051
I started asking them if
they wanted to, you know,

56:12.053 --> 56:15.391
Write and it was like this
kind of communal activity,

56:15.392 --> 56:18.819
And it's turned from that thing
that it was into what it is now,

56:18.825 --> 56:21.555
Which is my little
intros and then a piece.

56:21.561 --> 56:23.631
I mean, it could be by me
or by any one of a...

56:23.632 --> 56:26.499
I think a pretty
striking set of writers.

56:38.407 --> 56:40.507
The establishment reporters,
without a doubt,

56:40.509 --> 56:42.478
Know a lot of things
I don't know,

56:42.479 --> 56:44.937
But a lot of what
they know isn't true.

56:44.946 --> 56:48.976
He was a fantastic
journalist and the...

56:48.982 --> 56:50.749
As he himself pointed out,

56:50.750 --> 56:53.418
The greatest contribution
to his career

56:53.419 --> 56:55.019
Was his being excluded.

56:56.320 --> 56:57.720
He didn't have,
as he pointed out,

56:57.722 --> 56:59.391
He didn't have to waste his time

56:59.392 --> 57:01.990
Going to press conferences
'cause he wasn't invited,

57:01.992 --> 57:04.692
So he didn't have to hear
all the deceit and the lies

57:04.694 --> 57:06.864
And so he didn't have to
waste his time repeating them.

57:06.865 --> 57:09.632
He could just go
straight to the documents,

57:09.633 --> 57:12.671
To the historical record,
see what's happening,

57:12.672 --> 57:14.497
And he did it brilliantly.

57:18.037 --> 57:19.697
Going in the
white house and going

57:19.706 --> 57:21.906
And asking questions
of the press secretary,

57:21.908 --> 57:23.938
It's a job that some
people have to do.

57:23.943 --> 57:27.612
It's not often that you develop
new information from doing that,

57:27.613 --> 57:30.413
And it just becomes
a battle of spins.

57:30.415 --> 57:31.875
I do remember going once

57:31.883 --> 57:34.851
And Ari Fleischer
was press secretary

57:34.852 --> 57:38.852
And he kept, just
saying the same thing.

57:38.855 --> 57:41.315
"No, it's true, it's true."

57:41.324 --> 57:44.094
I go, "but this report
just came out from wherever"

57:44.095 --> 57:46.963
And it says that actually
that didn't happen."

57:46.964 --> 57:49.200
And he goes,
"no, but it did happen."

57:49.201 --> 57:52.997
And I really felt like I was
talking to a guy who was saying,

57:53.000 --> 57:54.430
"the sky is green."

57:54.434 --> 57:56.734
And I would say, "no, no, no,
actually, the sky is blue."

57:56.736 --> 57:59.696
He goes, "no, no,
the sky is green."

57:59.705 --> 58:03.005
And you can only do that so
much, and people, you know,

58:03.008 --> 58:05.578
Who are on that side
will say, damn it is!

58:06.743 --> 58:08.813
We ask each nation
on the security council

58:08.814 --> 58:11.982
To weigh the merits that make
a decision about war and peace,

58:11.983 --> 58:15.850
And if anybody thinks that
there are nations, like Mexico,

58:15.851 --> 58:18.951
Whose vote could be bought
on the basis of a trade issue

58:18.954 --> 58:21.792
Or something else like that,
I think you're giving...

58:21.793 --> 58:24.320
Do a grave injustice
to the independence

58:24.325 --> 58:26.755
And the judgment of the
leaders of other nations.

58:26.760 --> 58:28.560
Think about the implications
what you're saying.

58:28.561 --> 58:31.631
You're saying that the leaders
of other nations are buy-able

58:31.632 --> 58:33.860
And that is not
an acceptable proposition.

58:37.001 --> 58:38.071
Thank you.

58:51.679 --> 58:53.609
Good afternoon, everybody.

58:53.615 --> 58:56.315
What concerns does
the president have

58:56.317 --> 59:00.386
About the possibility that
Donald trump could someday

59:00.387 --> 59:02.487
Be the us commander in chief?

59:02.489 --> 59:04.689
The president has confidence

59:04.691 --> 59:06.921
That if Mr. Trump is
the republican nominee,

59:06.926 --> 59:08.826
He will not win
the general election.

59:08.827 --> 59:11.287
It's kind of a, you know,
a bit of a kabuki,

59:11.296 --> 59:15.556
Theatrical production each day,
and so he's here facing,

59:15.566 --> 59:18.026
I don't know how
many reporters, 70...

59:18.035 --> 59:19.465
70 reporters or so,

59:19.469 --> 59:22.938
Who really want to
drive him off message,

59:22.939 --> 59:26.009
And so he has to come out
and seem more or less

59:26.010 --> 59:28.508
To be answering questions
without saying anything

59:28.510 --> 59:29.910
That's gonna make news.

59:29.911 --> 59:33.211
What is the president
hearing from us allies

59:33.214 --> 59:36.624
And those who participate
in us military operations

59:36.625 --> 59:38.217
Alongside Americans?

59:38.218 --> 59:40.918
I'm not gonna be able to
share any secret details

59:40.920 --> 59:43.120
Of conversations that
the president has had

59:43.122 --> 59:45.056
With other world leaders,

59:45.057 --> 59:47.917
But there are global
consequences for arguments

59:47.926 --> 59:50.086
That are made by
domestic politicians.

59:50.094 --> 59:52.194
But I think, you know,

59:52.196 --> 59:55.056
The white house should
recognize that the media,

59:55.065 --> 59:57.925
Which represents the public
to some degree, you know,

59:57.934 --> 59:59.734
Has the right to ask questions

59:59.735 --> 01:00:01.735
And that sometimes
they have to answer things

01:00:01.737 --> 01:00:03.367
That aren't really, maybe,

01:00:03.371 --> 01:00:06.141
What they most are interested
in talking about that day.

